calcium channels"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the cardiac action potential, \u003Cstrong\u003EL-type calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E open at a threshold of -40 mV, allowing increased calcium entry into cardiomyocytes. This influx of calcium ions is crucial for the plateau phase (phase 2) of the cardiac action potential and contributes to the contraction of cardiac muscle cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E  \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E are not a recognised type of calcium channel in cardiac physiology.\u003C/li\u003E  \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunny channels\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as HCN channels) are primarily involved in the spontaneous depolarisation of pacemaker cells and do not directly contribute to calcium entry.\u003C/li\u003E  \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-type calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily found in neurons and are not typically associated with cardiac action potentials.\u003C/li\u003E  \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET-type calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E are present in cardiac cells but activate at a lower threshold (around -70 mV) and are mainly involved in the pacemaker potential of nodal cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["L-type calcium channels open at a threshold of -40 mV during the cardiac action potential, allowing increased calcium entry into cardiomyocytes.","The opening of L-type calcium channels contributes to the plateau phase (phase 2) of the cardiac action potential."],"references":["Kushner J, Ferrer X, Marx SO. Roles and Regulation of Voltage-gated Calcium Channels in Arrhythmias. J Innov Card Rhythm Manag. 2019 Oct 15;10(10):3874-3880. doi: 10.19102/icrm.2019.101006. PMID: 32494407; PMCID: PMC7252866.","Shah VN, Chagot B, Chazin WJ. Calcium-Dependent Regulation of Ion Channels. Calcium Bind Proteins. 2006 Oct-Dec;1(4):203-212. PMID: 28757812; PMCID: PMC5531595.","Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40931"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14437"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40931"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-15T14:39:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T14:40:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7132"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55401"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name